WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.560
Without further ado, here's Mariah Meyer talking about designing effective visualizations.

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:17.360
Thank you so much.

00:00:17.360 --> 00:00:18.440
Thanks so much for being here.

00:00:18.440 --> 00:00:19.520
I'm super excited.

00:00:19.520 --> 00:00:23.000
This conference is very energizing and really awesome.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:24.840
I feel like I'm one of the cool kids.

00:00:24.840 --> 00:00:27.559
So yeah, let's go with that.

00:00:27.559 --> 00:00:32.799
So my name is Mariah, and I am a professor at the University of Utah, which is in beautiful

00:00:32.799 --> 00:00:34.919
Salt Lake City.

00:00:34.919 --> 00:00:40.200
And at the U, I get to work with an amazing group of students in the visualization design

00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:44.320
lab, which I co-run with my colleague Alex Lex.

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:50.959
Now in our lab, what we focus on is doing deeply collaborative, design-oriented visualization

00:00:50.959 --> 00:00:51.959
research.

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:57.160
And so what that means is that we spend a lot of time working very closely with domain

00:00:57.160 --> 00:01:02.279
experts in a wide variety of fields to really understand how they think about their data

00:01:02.279 --> 00:01:07.720
and to translate those needs and those mental models into effective design tools.

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:13.639
Now we work with data analysts from biology and neuroscience through cybersecurity and

00:01:13.639 --> 00:01:15.120
even poetry.

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:21.279
And as researchers, we use these projects as test beds for us to experiment and to ask

00:01:21.279 --> 00:01:23.480
research questions.

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:28.959
And so the kinds of questions that we ask as researchers can kind of bucket into three

00:01:28.959 --> 00:01:31.760
main classes of things.

00:01:31.760 --> 00:01:36.519
So the first one are questions about, you know, how can we use these collaborative projects

00:01:36.519 --> 00:01:42.599
to come up with new and innovative visualization designs that can help us better understand

00:01:42.599 --> 00:01:46.080
the increasingly complex data that we have?

00:01:46.080 --> 00:01:50.839
The second thing that we also ask questions about is about the visualization design process

00:01:50.919 --> 00:01:52.160
itself.

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:57.879
So how can we as visualization designers and practitioners do what we do more effectively

00:01:57.879 --> 00:02:00.360
and more efficiently?

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:05.040
And then the third thing we think a lot about, and one that I'm increasingly excited about,

00:02:05.040 --> 00:02:10.080
is really moving beyond thinking of visualization as the end product and to instead think of

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:14.800
it as a way to probe into how people think about their data and their relationship to

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:16.639
technology in general.

00:02:16.639 --> 00:02:22.039
And for me, this is really about using visualizations as a tool in the sort of human side of data

00:02:22.039 --> 00:02:23.039
science.

00:02:23.039 --> 00:02:29.139
So today, what I wanted to share with you were a couple of examples from projects about

00:02:29.139 --> 00:02:37.559
how we used ideas from the visualization research community in our very pragmatic design-oriented

00:02:37.559 --> 00:02:40.919
process that we also do as practitioners.

00:02:40.919 --> 00:02:45.600
And hopefully along the way, maybe give you guys a little bit of ideas how you can also

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:49.440
look to some of the visualization research as a way to change and shift the way that

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:51.759
you're approaching visualization design.

00:02:51.759 --> 00:02:57.839
All right, so to begin, let's talk a little bit about the idea of designing new and innovative

00:02:57.839 --> 00:03:00.279
visualization techniques.

00:03:00.279 --> 00:03:04.039
And here I want to talk to you about, I want to tell you about a project that I worked

00:03:04.039 --> 00:03:07.600
on with a colleague of mine, Bang Wong, who is in Boston.

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:10.639
He's a really brilliant visual designer.

00:03:10.639 --> 00:03:14.919
And Bang and I were working with a group of biologists who were studying yeast, or more

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:19.399
specifically, they were interested in the process of metabolism in yeast.

00:03:19.399 --> 00:03:26.880
Now this group was trying to understand how different species evolved a similar process

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:31.600
for metabolism because this actually has implications for our understanding of how diseases like

00:03:31.600 --> 00:03:33.679
cancer work.

00:03:33.679 --> 00:03:37.160
Now the main kind of data that this group was working with was something called gene

00:03:37.160 --> 00:03:41.399
expression, which is really just a measurement of how much a gene is turned on or off in

00:03:41.399 --> 00:03:42.600
a cell.

00:03:42.600 --> 00:03:46.919
And the group was collecting gene expression for many different species of yeast and under

00:03:46.919 --> 00:03:50.759
different experimental conditions.

00:03:50.759 --> 00:03:56.000
Now their main method for visualizing this data is a heat map, and this is in fact one

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:57.000
from theirs.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:02.399
And I can see Will in the front sort of tilting his head, and I'm sorry, I will never do that

00:04:02.399 --> 00:04:03.399
again.

00:04:03.399 --> 00:04:09.160
So, yeah, so, but a heat map is the predominant way that these biologists were looking at

00:04:09.160 --> 00:04:11.639
their gene expression data.

00:04:11.679 --> 00:04:18.239
So Bang and I began to engage these scientists in conversations around what worked well for

00:04:18.239 --> 00:04:22.320
them with this visualization, but really what was really problematic.

00:04:22.320 --> 00:04:27.799
And what they said is that they wanted to be able to make very fine-scale, nuanced decisions

00:04:27.799 --> 00:04:32.839
based upon changes in gene expression, and they found that in these heat maps it was

00:04:32.839 --> 00:04:37.279
nearly impossible to see that kind of detail of the data.

00:04:37.279 --> 00:04:41.119
So Bang and I stepped back and we said, okay, so we need to redesign a heat map, but how

00:04:41.119 --> 00:04:46.200
in the world do we start even approaching this problem of coming up with something new?

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:50.959
And so we decided to turn to a fundamental principle in visualization design, which is

00:04:50.959 --> 00:04:56.200
that spatial encoding is the most effective encoding channel that we have.

00:04:56.200 --> 00:05:00.239
So by spatial encoding, what I mean is by positioning marks on a common scale, such

00:05:00.239 --> 00:05:06.799
as in a scatter plot, or using the length of some sort of mark like we do in a bar chart.

00:05:06.799 --> 00:05:09.179
So okay, so this is a foundational principle.

00:05:09.260 --> 00:05:16.140
We can ask many visualization designers about this, but as a researcher, how do we actually

00:05:16.140 --> 00:05:20.299
know that this is a good principle to go by?

00:05:20.299 --> 00:05:24.260
And part of it we know through controlled studies that have been done looking at different

00:05:24.260 --> 00:05:28.540
encoding channels, the first of which was done by the statisticians Cleveland and McGill

00:05:28.540 --> 00:05:33.059
back in the 80s, when they did a controlled lab experiment where they ran participants

00:05:33.059 --> 00:05:37.619
through a series of tasks using different encodings like color, position, angle, and

00:05:37.619 --> 00:05:43.019
so on, and they found that the spatial encoding techniques significantly outperformed other

00:05:43.019 --> 00:05:45.820
types of visual encodings.

00:05:45.820 --> 00:05:52.420
Now this study was replicated a number of years ago by Jeff Hare and Mike Bostock, only

00:05:52.420 --> 00:05:55.500
this time they did it on Mechanical Turk, so they were reaching hundreds and hundreds

00:05:55.500 --> 00:06:01.859
of people, and the results that they got were very similar to what Cleveland and McGill

00:06:01.859 --> 00:06:04.380
had done in their studies.

00:06:04.380 --> 00:06:08.899
And so it's in studies like this that we're able to say with some confidence that certain

00:06:08.899 --> 00:06:14.420
kinds of visual encoding channels are more effective for certain kinds of tasks.

00:06:14.420 --> 00:06:21.079
And based on this, we can think about our basic encoding channels and rank order them.

00:06:21.079 --> 00:06:25.739
So for example, here what we're looking at on the left-hand side are encoding channels

00:06:25.739 --> 00:06:30.220
that we have for encoding quantitative data, and on the right-hand side are the basic encoding

00:06:30.220 --> 00:06:31.980
channels for categorical attributes.

00:06:31.980 --> 00:06:37.540
And you'll notice at the top, both of them have spatial encoding as the highest-ranked

00:06:37.540 --> 00:06:38.980
one.

00:06:38.980 --> 00:06:43.700
So as visualization researchers, we take studies, we do studies on a variety of things like

00:06:43.700 --> 00:06:47.820
basic visual encoding channels, but we also combine it with things that we learn from

00:06:47.820 --> 00:06:52.899
design practice and years and years of anecdotal evidence to get to ideas like this.

00:06:52.899 --> 00:06:57.380
All right, so back to the yeast.

00:06:57.380 --> 00:07:01.859
So when Beng and I, we decided, okay, so let's take this principle and let's think about,

00:07:02.739 --> 00:07:04.700
well, what does that mean in terms of the data we have?

00:07:04.700 --> 00:07:08.700
And we decided, okay, well, the data we have is actually time series, so let's look at

00:07:08.700 --> 00:07:10.500
line charts.

00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:14.739
So we went off in an illustrator, we mocked up every single variation that we could possibly

00:07:14.739 --> 00:07:18.859
think of for how to show a line chart, and we printed it out on a big poster, and what

00:07:18.859 --> 00:07:23.339
we noticed was the one over here on the right, these little filled frame charts, really made

00:07:23.339 --> 00:07:26.820
the shape of those line charts pop out.

00:07:26.820 --> 00:07:31.299
And so we incorporated that idea into a new technique that we called a curve map that

00:07:31.299 --> 00:07:37.779
we implemented as part of a bigger multi-view system that we deployed to our collaborators.

00:07:37.779 --> 00:07:43.059
Now using this new curve map technique, our collaborators said that they were able to

00:07:43.059 --> 00:07:47.739
much more quickly see nuanced things that they knew about the data, but they also saw

00:07:47.739 --> 00:07:52.179
things that they had never known were there, which led to follow-up experiments and the

00:07:52.179 --> 00:07:57.000
discovery of some new scientific concepts that they weren't aware of before.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:05.359
So in this way, I want to stress that this idea is that we can take ideas about perceptual

00:08:05.359 --> 00:08:09.779
principles and other things and use those as a way to brainstorm and sort of a springboard

00:08:09.779 --> 00:08:14.040
for thinking about new ways to encode our own data.

00:08:14.040 --> 00:08:19.880
Okay, the second point, the visualization design process.

00:08:19.880 --> 00:08:24.079
So here is really about saying, okay, well, we have to create visualizations, but there's

00:08:24.079 --> 00:08:27.959
a whole lot of stuff we have to do before that, which is even figuring out what is it

00:08:27.959 --> 00:08:30.640
that I want to visualize in my data.

00:08:30.640 --> 00:08:34.119
And this is one of the things that I personally have spent a lot of time on and care about

00:08:34.119 --> 00:08:35.119
a lot.

00:08:35.119 --> 00:08:40.520
So I'm going to start with a little flavor of what it's like to be a visualization researcher

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:41.520
like myself.

00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:44.239
So we have two people, a viz person and a biologist.

00:08:44.239 --> 00:08:48.479
We might start by saying, oh, what is it you want to visualize?

00:08:48.479 --> 00:08:52.400
And the biologist might say something like, well, from patterns of conservation, we want

00:08:52.400 --> 00:08:55.679
to visualize the mechanisms that influence gene regulation.

00:08:55.679 --> 00:08:59.520
And to me, it sounds like this.

00:08:59.520 --> 00:09:03.200
So it turns out the ginger effect isn't just for debugging.

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:06.000
It also occurs all the time in visualization design.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:12.479
And as a side note, beware of Jenny Bryan scooping your punch lines.

00:09:12.479 --> 00:09:17.320
But I am just going to plow ahead anyway.

00:09:17.320 --> 00:09:18.960
Thanks, Jenny.

00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:19.960
Okay.

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:21.479
So but it's true.

00:09:21.559 --> 00:09:27.200
That same experience about only really like seeing a few things at a time is absolutely

00:09:27.200 --> 00:09:30.640
the case when we jump into these new projects.

00:09:30.640 --> 00:09:36.280
What I'm really interested is in how we get from a very semantically rich like task like

00:09:36.280 --> 00:09:42.719
we have here to the knowledge that we can then design a visualization like this to support.

00:09:42.719 --> 00:09:48.599
So fundamental to this process is identifying something I like to call proxies, which are

00:09:48.760 --> 00:09:54.320
the partial and imperfect data representation of that semantically rich thing that the analyst

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:56.799
actually cares about.

00:09:56.799 --> 00:10:02.359
The high level goals of a data analyst is actually rarely captured directly in the data.

00:10:02.359 --> 00:10:06.859
And if it was, you probably wouldn't need visualization anyway.

00:10:06.859 --> 00:10:09.960
So instead, what we have to spend a lot of time doing is thinking about what are the

00:10:09.960 --> 00:10:17.159
things in my data that I can infer something from that will then actually let me answer

00:10:17.159 --> 00:10:18.840
the question I have.

00:10:18.840 --> 00:10:22.320
And so let me give you an example of what I mean by this.

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:26.799
Let's say that I wanted to identify good film directors because I don't know, Sundance is

00:10:26.799 --> 00:10:30.960
happening right now in Salt Lake and I'm a journalist and I need to identify some good

00:10:30.960 --> 00:10:31.960
film directors.

00:10:31.960 --> 00:10:32.960
Okay.

00:10:32.960 --> 00:10:33.960
Great.

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:37.280
So I go off and I scrape some data from IMDb about movies.

00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:40.919
So now I have this data set that includes lots of information about movies such as how

00:10:40.919 --> 00:10:43.919
much money they've made, their ratings and so on.

00:10:43.919 --> 00:10:44.919
Wonderful.

00:10:45.200 --> 00:10:49.520
But now going back to my question, my question is really about film directors, but I have

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:51.320
information about movies.

00:10:51.320 --> 00:10:53.799
So what do I do?

00:10:53.799 --> 00:10:57.599
And this is where I like to think about this notion of how do I select a good proxy in

00:10:57.599 --> 00:10:59.719
my data for my question.

00:10:59.719 --> 00:11:02.760
And so my colleague Danielle Fisher and I came up with this very simple mechanism for

00:11:02.760 --> 00:11:06.679
doing this, which is we break a task down into three things.

00:11:06.679 --> 00:11:10.400
Into the action, which is the thing you want to do.

00:11:10.400 --> 00:11:14.479
Into the object, which is the items you want to take that action on.

00:11:15.039 --> 00:11:18.840
And then finally, the measure, which is the value that you care about for those objects.

00:11:18.840 --> 00:11:21.919
And so if we do this, let's look at our tasks.

00:11:21.919 --> 00:11:23.440
So the action is identifying.

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:25.400
What do I want to identify?

00:11:25.400 --> 00:11:27.000
Film directors.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:31.719
Now this is where I know that I have a data set about movies, not film directors, but

00:11:31.719 --> 00:11:35.719
I could say if I can learn something about movies, I can infer something about directors.

00:11:35.719 --> 00:11:39.080
So I'm going to choose movies as my proxy for director.

00:11:39.080 --> 00:11:40.080
And what do I want to know?

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:42.440
I want to know if they're good.

00:11:42.440 --> 00:11:47.039
And now, you know, I don't have an attribute labeled good in my spreadsheet.

00:11:47.039 --> 00:11:51.599
So this is where I think all the time in data science, we are constantly making decisions

00:11:51.599 --> 00:11:55.880
that are inherently subjective and really specific for the one, for the, whatever the

00:11:55.880 --> 00:11:58.359
view is on the problem you're tackling.

00:11:58.359 --> 00:12:01.719
So in this case, good could be movies that make a lot of money.

00:12:01.719 --> 00:12:04.039
It could be movies that reach a broad demographic.

00:12:04.039 --> 00:12:07.760
But for now, I'm going to keep it simple and just say it's good equals movies with high

00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:10.119
IMDB ratings.

00:12:10.119 --> 00:12:15.679
So by identifying my proxies, I can now translate my task into something, identify movies with

00:12:15.679 --> 00:12:21.359
high IMDB ratings, which is actually something I can design a visualization or other sort

00:12:21.359 --> 00:12:24.640
of analysis to tackle.

00:12:24.640 --> 00:12:28.159
But it turns out that actually being able to do this translation and being able to find

00:12:28.159 --> 00:12:32.859
these proxies is a really challenging process and takes a lot of time.

00:12:32.859 --> 00:12:37.320
And in our group, what we do is we spend a lot of time really immersing ourselves with

00:12:37.320 --> 00:12:40.559
the people that we're working with in order to better understand the kinds of challenges

00:12:40.559 --> 00:12:44.200
they face and the things that they want to do.

00:12:44.200 --> 00:12:48.280
And some colleagues at the University of Calgary just this past year formalized this notion

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:53.640
of immersion by calling it design through immersion and talking about some of the sorts

00:12:53.640 --> 00:13:01.239
of benefits that we get when we do transdisciplinary kind of research and bring sort of big tent

00:13:01.239 --> 00:13:07.440
style approach to how we problem solve and in this case do data analysis.

00:13:07.440 --> 00:13:08.440
Okay.

00:13:08.440 --> 00:13:16.000
So that's a little bit about the visualization design process and how we can do that in practice.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.719
And then the last thing I want to talk about here is the notion of visualizations as probes.

00:13:19.719 --> 00:13:25.200
I'm going to do this by talking about another project that I worked on that was headed up

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:29.840
by a former student of mine, Nina McCurdy, where we were working with a group of public

00:13:29.840 --> 00:13:34.599
health experts at USAID who were studying Zika, the spread of Zika in Latin America

00:13:34.599 --> 00:13:39.119
and all the effects, notably microcephaly in babies.

00:13:39.119 --> 00:13:44.400
And so during this project, Nina spent six months at the USAID working closely with the

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:46.080
health experts there.

00:13:46.080 --> 00:13:50.239
And it had all the makings of a straightforward visualization project.

00:13:50.239 --> 00:13:52.080
The collaborators had data.

00:13:52.080 --> 00:13:55.919
They had tried to visualize their data and failed and so they were super excited to work

00:13:55.919 --> 00:13:56.919
with us.

00:13:56.919 --> 00:13:59.599
And so Nina left and we dug in.

00:13:59.640 --> 00:14:04.400
Now, over the course of the study, Nina did a lot of rapid prototyping and ultimately

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:11.880
designed a tool that used best practices for how we can incorporate all sorts of tabular

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:15.799
data with geospatial information.

00:14:15.799 --> 00:14:21.159
She evaluated this tool with various stakeholders throughout that time and the response was

00:14:21.159 --> 00:14:27.799
overwhelmingly positive, that this was a great tool for the data that they had.

00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:33.320
And yet, when we tried to engage our immediate collaborators in incorporating the tool as

00:14:33.320 --> 00:14:38.640
part of their workflow, we noticed a lot of hesitation and we were really concerned about

00:14:38.640 --> 00:14:39.840
this.

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:44.599
And as we probed deeper into this hesitation, we came to understand that even though the

00:14:44.599 --> 00:14:49.679
tool was a good representation of their data, the data was not a good representation of

00:14:49.679 --> 00:14:54.799
what they knew to be true about the spread of Zika on the ground.

00:14:54.799 --> 00:14:59.000
So this first came up in a discussion of a choropleth that looked like this one showing

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.559
Zika cases at a national level.

00:15:01.559 --> 00:15:05.640
So as you'll see here, Brazil is in dark red, indicating a relatively high percentage of

00:15:05.640 --> 00:15:11.280
cases, whereas Colombia is in a lighter orange, indicating a relatively lower percentage.

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:16.679
Now, one of our collaborators, when she saw this, she noted, well, Brazil reports all

00:15:16.679 --> 00:15:22.159
cases, whereas Colombia only reports cases after a thorough investigation.

00:15:22.400 --> 00:15:28.440
The implication of this comment was that the different ways in which these countries were

00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:33.960
reporting Zika was leading to an inaccurate and possibly misleading picture of what was

00:15:33.960 --> 00:15:35.760
actually happening.

00:15:35.760 --> 00:15:40.320
So we pivoted to focus on this problem and found that the data was littered with discrepancies

00:15:40.320 --> 00:15:41.960
like this.

00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:46.799
And then in the case of Zika data, this came from the way that the data was collected and

00:15:46.799 --> 00:15:49.039
processed and reported.

00:15:49.039 --> 00:15:54.159
And it was this distributed heterogeneous data generation pipeline that occurred differently

00:15:54.159 --> 00:15:58.919
in every country that led to all these discrepancies.

00:15:58.919 --> 00:16:01.000
And now, you know, all was not lost.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:06.760
So even though these problems with the data were not included in the data set, the experts

00:16:06.760 --> 00:16:12.679
working with it had deep and intimate knowledge about them.

00:16:12.679 --> 00:16:17.880
And these discrepancies, it turns out, were shaped by the individual country's political,

00:16:17.919 --> 00:16:22.479
cultural, economic, geographic, and demographic context.

00:16:22.479 --> 00:16:27.159
And so we'd get discrepancies like the union in Region X goes on strike often and doesn't

00:16:27.159 --> 00:16:29.359
report Zika data.

00:16:29.359 --> 00:16:35.000
Or country Y recently overhauled its surveillance system, leading to a sudden increase in detected

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:36.640
cases.

00:16:36.640 --> 00:16:41.039
So in thinking about this, we formalized this notion into what we called implicit error,

00:16:41.039 --> 00:16:45.359
which is measurement error that is inherent to a given data set, assumed to be present

00:16:45.359 --> 00:16:49.640
and prevalent, but not explicitly defined or accounted for.

00:16:49.640 --> 00:16:54.080
And so we were able to characterize aspects of implicit error, as well as then design

00:16:54.080 --> 00:16:59.080
an annotation mechanism to help experts externalize.

00:16:59.080 --> 00:17:04.920
Nina implemented this annotation mechanism back into our tool, which we deployed back

00:17:04.920 --> 00:17:10.079
out so that these health experts could start annotating their data in order to share information

00:17:10.079 --> 00:17:14.760
with their colleagues, as well as to start to build up a database of contextual information

00:17:14.760 --> 00:17:18.439
around that initial data set.

00:17:18.439 --> 00:17:24.520
So although this work was grounded in Zika health data, we suspect that this type of

00:17:24.520 --> 00:17:28.000
implicit error is prevalent in many, many other domains.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:33.839
Okay, so this was an example where we were able to use visualization, not as necessarily

00:17:33.839 --> 00:17:38.800
the end result, but as a conversation starter about challenges that the group was having

00:17:38.800 --> 00:17:44.479
with the data, and then ultimately use visualization as a sort of mechanism to help analysts externalize

00:17:44.479 --> 00:17:49.479
things that they knew that wasn't captured in that data set.

00:17:49.479 --> 00:17:55.439
So these are three things that are the flavor of things that as visualization design researchers

00:17:55.439 --> 00:17:59.800
we think a lot about, and I think has a lot of impact about how we do visualization in

00:17:59.800 --> 00:18:01.959
practice.

00:18:01.959 --> 00:18:07.880
And I just wanted to leave with a quick recommended reading list.

00:18:07.880 --> 00:18:12.040
The first one maybe some of you know is Data Visualization by Noah Alinsky.

00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:15.599
It's a great book that I think incorporates a lot of the foundational principles that

00:18:15.599 --> 00:18:20.119
we in the research community have for designing visualizations.

00:18:20.119 --> 00:18:25.040
The next one, Visualization Analysis and Design, is the grad textbook by Tamara Munzner.

00:18:25.040 --> 00:18:30.760
If you want to geek out about how we talk about visualizations, as well as more complex

00:18:30.760 --> 00:18:33.380
visualization types, this is a great book.

00:18:33.380 --> 00:18:37.959
The next one, Making Data Visual, is a personal little plug, but this is a book that my colleague

00:18:37.959 --> 00:18:42.319
Danielle Fisher and I recently published that really looks at the process of how we

00:18:42.319 --> 00:18:44.520
figure out what we're designing for.

00:18:44.520 --> 00:18:48.439
And then the last one is the sort of sleeper recommendation, and this is a hand-me-down

00:18:48.439 --> 00:18:54.719
recommendation from Martin Wattenberg, which is a book that will absolutely change the

00:18:54.719 --> 00:18:57.719
way that you think about visualizations, and actually nicely complements a lot of what

00:18:57.719 --> 00:19:00.640
Will was talking about earlier today.

00:19:00.640 --> 00:19:02.680
And with that, I just want to thank you all for your attention.

00:19:07.959 --> 00:19:13.560
Thanks so much, Mariah.

00:19:13.560 --> 00:19:14.560
Some questions.

00:19:14.560 --> 00:19:20.280
Well, since you just mentioned him, was Martin Wattenberg right when he said pie charts were

00:19:20.280 --> 00:19:22.239
underrated?

00:19:22.239 --> 00:19:23.959
I absolutely agree.

00:19:23.959 --> 00:19:28.680
I totally agree that they're underrated, but this is a deep philosophical debate within

00:19:28.680 --> 00:19:30.400
the Viz community for sure.

00:19:30.400 --> 00:19:31.400
Great.

00:19:31.400 --> 00:19:33.400
Thanks for tackling that.

00:19:33.400 --> 00:19:38.359
Can you describe the many multiples chart you used to replace the gene expression heat

00:19:38.359 --> 00:19:39.359
map?

00:19:39.359 --> 00:19:40.920
What is shown on each axis?

00:19:40.920 --> 00:19:43.599
Did the final chart have more annotation?

00:19:43.599 --> 00:19:44.599
More annotation.

00:19:44.599 --> 00:19:45.599
Interesting.

00:19:45.599 --> 00:19:50.920
Yeah, so what we were showing is actually the rows were different species, the columns

00:19:50.920 --> 00:19:55.280
were different genes, and then we were looking at they had taken experimental measurements

00:19:55.280 --> 00:19:58.760
at different points during the life cycle of species, so that's what the time curves

00:19:58.760 --> 00:19:59.760
were.

00:19:59.760 --> 00:20:03.760
And really, the curve map gives you a table layout, so you can define attributes along

00:20:03.760 --> 00:20:10.520
the rows and the columns to help facet your data, and inside we were showing time curves.

00:20:10.520 --> 00:20:14.520
How do you bridge the knowledge gap to someone who might not understand or have ever seen

00:20:14.520 --> 00:20:16.239
a visualization like you've shown?

00:20:16.239 --> 00:20:17.239
Oh my gosh.

00:20:17.239 --> 00:20:18.239
Okay.

00:20:18.239 --> 00:20:19.239
I don't know how to answer that quickly.

00:20:19.239 --> 00:20:20.839
That's a great question.

00:20:20.839 --> 00:20:25.359
You know, what we actually do, and I think this is a really important point actually,

00:20:25.359 --> 00:20:29.359
is when we are designing a very new and different type of visualization, we don't just show

00:20:29.359 --> 00:20:32.280
up one day and say, voila, look, you're going to love it.

00:20:32.280 --> 00:20:35.839
But instead, it's a process of actually building trust with our colleagues so that they trust

00:20:35.839 --> 00:20:38.160
us with their hard-earned data.

00:20:38.160 --> 00:20:41.959
We often, the first thing we implement is similar to what they already have and slowly

00:20:41.959 --> 00:20:43.719
change things over time.

00:20:43.719 --> 00:20:46.119
We're actually designing with them, not for them.

00:20:46.119 --> 00:20:50.640
And so that collaborative process, I think that really helps people embrace new and different

00:20:50.640 --> 00:20:53.359
ways of looking at data.

00:20:53.359 --> 00:20:57.160
How do you determine the effectiveness of various visualization methods?

00:20:57.160 --> 00:20:58.439
Any qualitative metrics?

00:20:58.520 --> 00:20:59.520
Oh, yeah.

00:20:59.520 --> 00:21:00.520
Oh, wow.

00:21:00.520 --> 00:21:01.520
Great question.

00:21:01.520 --> 00:21:05.599
Some of the basic encoding channels I talked about are things that I think are pretty straightforward

00:21:05.599 --> 00:21:08.959
to be able to test quantitatively in a controlled experiment.

00:21:08.959 --> 00:21:11.680
It's largely based on our perceptual system.

00:21:11.680 --> 00:21:15.439
The kinds of visualizations that we create in my research group, though, are complex

00:21:15.439 --> 00:21:19.520
and part of the broader workflow, and we cannot test quantitatively.

00:21:19.520 --> 00:21:23.680
And so we use a lot of qualitative methods, such as case studies and other sorts of things,

00:21:23.680 --> 00:21:26.760
in order to understand the efficacy of the kinds of tools that we create.

00:21:26.800 --> 00:21:30.199
So, yeah, definitely we rely heavily on qualitative methods.

