Because I read them.

00:22:05.280 --> 00:22:06.280
Third one.

00:22:06.280 --> 00:22:07.280
Oh, is it well-acknowledged?

00:22:07.280 --> 00:22:08.280
Yeah.

00:22:08.280 --> 00:22:09.280
No.

00:22:09.280 --> 00:22:16.479
Especially when creating these kinds of visualizations that we often put out and that people use

00:22:16.479 --> 00:22:22.920
as part of a larger analysis pipeline, visualizations, I think, are woefully undersighted and has

00:22:22.920 --> 00:22:26.719
often led to a crisis within our research community about, like, what's the value of

00:22:26.719 --> 00:22:28.119
what we do?

00:22:28.119 --> 00:22:30.199
Because a lot of times it's not really acknowledged.

00:22:30.199 --> 00:22:34.800
I think visualizations are often used for creativity and brainstorming to get us thinking

00:22:34.800 --> 00:22:38.079
about something else we want to do, not necessarily for the final answer.

00:22:38.079 --> 00:22:42.640
And I think that part is something people don't necessarily recognize as an important

00:22:42.640 --> 00:22:43.640
thing to cite.

